<TITLE> Christmas prayer is for peace, fair polls </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 25 (bdnews24.com)  Christmas prayers across the country this year, as the election draws near, were for a peaceful vote on Dec. 29, with the Archbishop of Dhaka calling on all to play a role for free and fair polls. "Let us play a role from respective positions so that the December 29 election is a free and fair one and we can choose honest and competent candidates through voting," the Archbishop of Dhaka Paulinus Costa said on Thursday. The Christian community taking part in prayers at over 500 churches across the country mainly wished for a peaceful election, he said at a special reception for journalists at the Archbishop's Palace in Kakrail. Costa also wished Christmas greetings to people of all faiths. The president hosted a Christmas reception at Bangabhaban, which was attended by the archbishop who had earlier held the main Christmas Day service at Kakrail Church. President Iajuddin Ahmed and chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed issued separate messages on Christmas Eve Wednesday. "May happiness and festivity prevail in the life Christian community and all others on Christmas Day," the president wished. The chief adviser in his message, stressed: "We must always be alert in maintaining communal harmony in Bangladesh." Churches throughout the capital were seen adorned with lights and Christmas decorations from Christmas Eve, culminating in midnight mass to usher in Christmas Day. The main midnight mass was held at the Ramna Cathedral and conducted by Archbishop Costa though the largest congregation of four to five thousand is traditionally seen at Tejgaon Church. AL president Sheikh Hasina and BNP chairperson Khaleda Zia also issued messages stressing religious tolerance and communal harmony. Sheikh Hasina said her party was pledge bound to safeguard the rights of all people irrespective of their faith, while Khaleda Zia noted that Bangladesh was a remarkable example of religious tolerance. bdnews2
